        <h2>Practical Driving Considerations</h2>
        <p>Icelandic weather can change rapidly, making flexible planning essential. Check weather and road conditions daily through official sources, and be prepared to adjust routes or timing based on conditions. Wind can be particularly challenging, especially for high-profile vehicles.</p>

        <p>Fuel planning is crucial, as gas stations can be sparse in remote areas. Fill up whenever possible and carry emergency supplies including food, water, and warm clothing. GPS devices may not always be reliable, so carry physical maps as backup.</p>

        <p>Respect for Iceland's fragile environment is essential. Stay on marked paths, don't drive off-road, and follow Leave No Trace principles. Iceland's moss and vegetation can take decades to recover from damage, making environmental responsibility crucial.</p>

        <h2>Photography and Northern Lights</h2>
        <p>Iceland offers incredible photography opportunities throughout the year, with dramatic landscapes, changing weather, and unique lighting conditions. Golden hour light can last for hours during summer, while winter provides opportunities for Northern Lights photography.</p>

        <p>Northern Lights viewing requires dark skies, clear weather, and solar activity. Winter months (September through March) provide the best opportunities, with peak viewing typically between 9 PM and 2 AM. Apps and websites provide aurora forecasts and cloud cover predictions.</p>

        <p>Photography equipment should include weather protection, extra batteries (cold drains batteries quickly), and sturdy tripods for long exposures. The dramatic landscapes and changing conditions provide endless opportunities for compelling images.</p>

